In <3672hr$dvb@netnews.upenn.edu>, mlief@mail2.sas.upenn.edu (Michael Lief) writes:
>
>Why does everything seem to revolve around Windows? ... it
>seems that most popular titles are "for Windows," which seems to mean that
>OS/2 must emulate Windows to run them. Why is there not industry support
>(software) to make titles "for OS/2"? 
>
OS/2 has four API's.  Programs can use DOS conventions, Windows 3.x,
OS/2 1.x (16 bit), and 32-bit OS/2.  The Warp release will also support
WIN32S.   In addition, EMX provides something of a Unix-like API.

However, OS/2 applications can be written to use Fullscreen, VIO, or PM
services.  There is also an X-windows client with Motif.  Of course,
DOS programs write to the screen with BIOS calls, and Windows programs
use GDI.

Some say that one of the interfaces in OS/2 is less legitimate than some
other interface.  This is a type of puritanism that we can do without.
In their terms, an "native OS/2 program" is a program that can't run
on any other system.  Why?  In these terms, we have to dump all the
16-bit OS/2 programs because they are also supported by Windows NT 3.5.

I want good programs that work well and exploit the options that the
system provides.  Where appropriate, I would hope that a program makes
use of multithreading.  WPS integration is also nice.  In individual cases,
an OS/2 application can demonstrate more function and better service
than any corresponding Windows program.

But while it is possible to write "Hello World" using DosOpen, DosWrite,
and DosClose, nobody would claim that a "native" OS/2 version of the
program is better than the original that used plain "printf".  Some
programs just don't need anything more than what they already have.

The best feature of OS/2 is that it supports everything.  If you like
NETBIOS, BSD Sockets, WINSOCK, DCE, APPC, named pipes, or whatever,
its in there.  Now Sockets started out on Unix.  NETBIOS is a DOS interface.
APPC comes from the mainframe.   DCE is clearly from Unix.  So, if you
toss out all the stuff that isn't "native OS/2", what do you end up with?
See no Windows.  Hear no Windows.  Speak no Windows.
See no Unix.  Hear no Unix.  Speak no Unix.
Who cares?
