This is a major concern for me, as well.  I've been tasked with helping to 
define what our next "default" desktop operating system should be around 
here.  My bias towards OS/2 is well known, but I'm hesitating to recommend it 
for pretty much this same reason.

I think part of it lies in the fact that OS/2 does too damn good at 
running Windows apps, so a lot of major ISVs figure "why bother?"  A classic 
example is Borland:  Shortly after OS/2 2.0 came out, Phillipe Kahn pledged 
his support to OS/2, saying "We made Windows apps, but we didn't inhale."  A 
couple years later, Borland is cranking out Windows desktop apps, with nary a 
port to OS/2.  I got to ask Phillipe about this at an opening of a new Fry's 
a few months back, and he said "Our Windows applications run just fine under 
OS/2."  It appears that to some minds, IBM did their job too well, and 
removed the incentive to write native OS/2 apps.  So, you get attitudes like 
Borland's, or WordPerfect, who closed down their WP for OS/2 project as the 
code for version 6.0 was nearing completion.

Fortunately, not everyone thinks that way.  Lotus has a version of their 
SmartSuite (Ami Pro, 1-2-3, Freelance) for OS/2, and there are a number of 
smaller companies that are writing for OS/2 as well.  Around here, CompUSA is 
the best place to look for OS/2 titles, with Egghead a somewhat distant 
second.  If you're interested in mailorder, Indelible Blue (800-776-8284 for 
a catalog) carries virtually every title for OS/2.

 - Bob

